(110, 2, '2015-11-04 20:49:37', '2015-11-04 20:49:37', '<h2>Types of Life Insurance</h2>\r\nWhile <strong>term life insurance</strong> is the most common form, it is only one of the two main kinds. The other is <strong>permanent life insuranc</strong><strong>e</strong>, also known as <strong>whole life insurance</strong>. Both forms provide a payout on the death of the covered individual, but they are structured very differently in other ways.\r\n<h2>Understanding Term Life Insurance</h2>\r\nThe key to understanding <strong>term life insurance </strong>is in the word "<strong>term</strong>." When you buy a term life insurance policy, it has a fixed start and end date, which can be anywhere from 10 to 30 years apart. All you have to do is pay your regular monthly premium for the duration of the term.\r\n\r\nThe only catch is that once the policy expires, it is gone and you are no longer covered. In that way, it''s much like your regular car insurance.\r\n<h4>Advantages of Term Life Insurance</h4>\r\n*<strong>Term life insurance is simple</strong>, you don''t have to worry about complexities hidden in the fine print\r\n\r\n*<strong>Term life insurance is affordable</strong>. It''s easy to fit into almost any budget\r\n\r\n*<strong>Term life insurance can be cancelled before the term expires</strong> if your situation changes\r\n<h4>Limitations of Term Life Insurance</h4>\r\n*Your coverage expires at the end of the term\r\n\r\n*If you still need insurance after your policy expires, you need to either convert your existing plan to a permanent one or start looking around for a new one\r\n<h2>Permanent Life Insurance</h2>\r\n<strong>Permanent life insurance</strong>, on the other hand, works differently. First, it has an indefinite term. You have insurance as long as you pay the premiums, <strong>because the policy never expires</strong>. The second important difference is that permanent life insurance has a <strong>cash value</strong>.\r\n\r\nThis means a permanent life insurance policy is an asset. If you need money, you can borrow against it; you can even cancel the policy and take the money. It''s more flexible but also more complicated.\r\n<h4>Advantages of Permanent Life Insurance</h4>\r\n*<strong>It is an asset</strong>. This means you can use it as part of your overall financial strategy\r\n\r\n*<strong>It does not expire</strong>. You don''t have to worry about needing to get a new policy\r\n<h4>Disadvantages of Permanent Life Insurance</h4>\r\n*<strong>Complexity</strong>. It is more complicated than term life insurance, so it can be more difficult to choose the right policy\r\n\r\n*<strong>Price</strong>. It costs more because the insurance company is more likely to have to pay out. This also means many people may carry less coverage than they really need\r\n\r\n*<strong>Value</strong>. While it is an asset, both the cash value and premium costs can fluctuate for reasons outside your control\r\n<h2>Picking the Right Life Insurance Type</h2>\r\nWhen it comes to picking the right life insurance type for your needs, there are two main things to consider: your needs, and your budget. If both are simple, go with <strong>term life insurance</strong>. If your situation is more complex, you may benefit more from <strong>permanent life insurance</strong>. There is no wrong choice, only the one that is best for you.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Life Insurance Guide (Part II) - Term vs. Whole Life', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-is-life-insurance-part-2', '', '', '2015-11-05 20:02:46', '2015-11-05 20:02:46', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8771/nia/?p=110', 0, 'post', '', 0),
