raction of the average monthly health insurance bill\r\n<h2>Picking the Right Life Insurance Policy</h2>\r\nThe most important thing to remember about life insurance is that <strong>no one policy fits everyone. </strong>Most people can do just fine with a simple term life insurance policy, but if you need more, there are more complex plans available that can cover a wide variety of factors including:\r\n\r\n*Estate Planning\r\n\r\n*Minimizing Tax Expenses\r\n\r\n*Providing for Charitable Donations\r\n<div>Find the policy that''s right for you, and don''t be afraid to change it when your needs change.</div>', 'Life Insurance Guide (Part I) - Life Insurance Basics', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '104-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-11-05 20:03:29', '2015-11-05 20:03:29', '', 104, 'http://localhost:8771/nia/104-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(117, 2, '2015-11-05 20:50:06', '2015-11-05 20:50:06', 'Even though <strong>term life insurance</strong> is easy to understand in principle, not all policies have the same features, and it''s important to understand how the different features work so you can choose the policy that''s right for  you.\r\n<h2>Policy Length</h2>\r\nOne of the most important features to look at when buying term life insurance is the length of your policy. You can buy term life insurance in terms as short as one year, or as long as twenty or thirty years depending on your provider.\r\n<h4>Why Choose a Longer Policy?</h4>\r\n*Cost control. The younger you are when you get a policy, the lower the premiums. Buying a longer policy keeps the rate under control.\r\n<h4>Why Choose a Shorter Policy?</h4>\r\n*To match your needs. Many people buy life insurance to cover expenses such as a car loan or a mortgage. If you only have a five year car loan, you don''t need a ten year policy to cover it.\r\n<h2>Other Features</h2>\r\nWhile policy length is the most important feature for a life insurance policy, it is not the only one to consider.\r\n<h4>Grace Period</h4>\r\n*Many policies come with a grace period of perhaps 30 days, so that the policy remains valid even if you cannot pay it in time. This is very useful in cases of sudden death where it may take some time to figure out all the payments that still have to be made.\r\n<h4>Guaranteed Premium</h4>\r\n*Not all premiums remain constant for the life of the policy. A guaranteed premium rate ensures that your premium stays the same for as long as you hold the policy.\r\n<h4>Guaranteed Renewal</h4>\r\n*This lets you extend or renew your policy without the need for another medical exam. It''s usually only available for people under 40, but it really helps reduce the time it takes to get a new policy approved.\r\n<h4>Guaranteed Incontestability</h4>\r\n*Protect your policy, with guaranteed incontestability. This feature means that after an initial period, usually two years, your insurer cannot just cancel the policy without evidence of deliberate fraud. You still have to make your payments, though.\r\n\r\nAlways take the time to learn the details of any contract you may be signing. It''s better for everyone.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Life Insurance Guide (Part III) - Term Life Insurance Features', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'life-insurance-guide-part-iii-term-life-insurance-features', '', '', '2015-11-05 20:50:06', '2015-11-05 20:50:06', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8771/nia/?p=117', 0, 'post', '', 0),
