(129, 2, '2015-11-09 20:25:24', '2015-11-09 20:25:24', 'So now that you understand the basics of life insurance, it''s time to take a look at a few examples. Each example shows how people in different situations can get the greatest benefit from different life insurance options. Theory is always useful, but there is nothing like seeing choices in action to get a greater understanding of how things work.\r\n<h2>Example 1: Tanisha</h2>\r\nTwenty-two year old Tanisha has just graduated from college and is starting her first real job. She has no significant assets, and her only liability is a $25,000 student loan, which her parents co-signed so she wouldn''t have to work for her final year of college. With a good job, she plans to pay off her student loan within five years.\r\n<h4>Tanisha''s Policy</h4>\r\nTanisha''s policy is a 5-year term policy, starting at $30,000, to cover her funeral expenses and pay off her student loan. If she wants, she can take out a "decreasing term" policy where the payout reduces over time. This lets her take advantage of her steadily decreasing student debt to lower her premiums. She''ll have less insurance as the term progresses because she won''t need as much near the end as she does now.\r\n<h2>Example 2: Ellen</h2>\r\nEllen is thirty-three years old, she and her husband Noah have two children, Marcus and Portia, aged nine and ten. Both Noah and Ellen work. They have savings, but they also just refinanced their house for $300,000 over 25 years. They got a good interest rate, but they''re still paying almost $25,000 a year. With two incomes, this isn''t bad, but it''s too much for either Ellen or Noah to manage on their own.\r\n<h4>Ellen''s Policy</h4>\r\nEllen''s policy, and Noah''s for that matter, because they each have the same amount of coverage, is a 25 year term policy for $1.2 million. After paying off the mortgage, about $600,000, the survivor should have about $600,000 for other expenses including putting both the kids through college.\r\n<h2>Example 3: Richard</h2>\r\nRichard is 48, married, and has two adult children who are out on their own. He is in a good position financially with a solid retirement savings plan, but still owes on his mortgage. He''s also partially responsible for the care of his elderly mother, who is currently in an assisted living situation. She has savings, but they may not be enough to cover things if her medical costs increase significantly.\r\n<h4>Richard''s Policy</h4>\r\nRichard''s policy is a 20 year term policy for $1.0 million. It is actually more money than his wife would be likely to need, but he went for the extra coverage so she can retire early after paying off the mortgage if she wants. It also provides a cushion in case his mother''s health care costs spike after he is no longer around to take care of them.\r\n\r\nNone of these policies are exactly the same, but they all serve the same basic function. They cover the policy holder''s most important responsibilities if they are no longer able. Yours should do the same.', 'Life Insurance Guide (Part V) - Life Insurance Examples', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'life-insurance-guide-part-v-life-insurance-examples', '', '', '2015-11-09 20:30:03', '2015-11-09 20:30:03', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8771/nia/?p=129', 0, 'post', '', 0),
