(154, 2, '2015-11-10 21:00:43', '2015-11-10 21:00:43', 'For many people, the scariest thing about buying <strong>life insurance</strong> is the application. You cannot simply walk into an office, plunk down your money, and walk out with a policy. It''s not like buying a TV, it''s a process. When you apply for life insurance, there are two main factors that the insurance company needs to consider: your financial health, and your physical health.\n\nFor the company, it''s all about managing risk. It is risking its money against your life, and the longer you live, the lower the risk.\n\nWhile it''s easiest to think about <strong>term life insurance</strong>, the basic procedures are the same for both term and <strong>permanent life insurance policies</strong>.\n\n<h2>About the Application</h2>\n\nThe first thing to remember when filling out your life insurance application is to <strong>tell the truth</strong>, especially when it comes to health questions. Your life insurance policy is a binding contract, and if you misrepresent yourself on the application then the contract is no longer valid. In other words, if you do not disclose your health conditions, your insurer may not pay the <strong>death benefit</strong>.\n\n<h2>Filling it Out</h2>\n\nInsurance companies maintain a huge library of statistical information about people that they use to determine risk and decide on policies and premiums, and the more information you give the company, the better it is able to determine your risk factors and what policies it can offer.\n\n<h4>The Life Insurance Application Form</h4>\n\nAs with any other application, the initial questions are very common. The company will want to know your:\n\n*Name\n\n*Address\n\n*Employer\n\n*Net Worth\n\nIn addition to that, the form will also ask a number of other, more personal questions.\n\n*Your Age\n\n*Your Height and Weight\n\n*Your Lifestyle and Exercise Habits\n\n*Your Smoking and Drinking Habits\n\nThere will also be space on the form for your medical information, but most of this will be covered in greater detail during the <strong>medical exam</strong>.\n\n<h4>The Life Insurance Medical Examination</h4>\n\nMost insurance companies require an independent medical examination before they will offer you a policy. They will usually send a professional to your home or business, or perhaps at a clinic of their choosing. Regardless of where it takes place, this is a reasonably thorough examination.\n\nIn most cases, the examiner will want at least the following from you:\n\n*A Blood Sample\n\n*A Urine Sample\n\n*Your Complete Medical History\n\n*Your Family Medical History\n\n*Your Height and Weight\n\n*Your Blood Pressure\n\n*Your Heart Rate\n\nThe examiner will also give you an interview, asking about your exercise habits, how much you drink or smoke, whether you have diabetes, and also what you do for recreation. In general, they will not only want to know how active you are, but also the type of activities you prefer.\n\nSome insurers may ask for a more complete examination. It depends on a number of factors including the amount of the policy, and especially your age. In general, the older you are, the more thorough the examination.\n\n<h2>After the Examination</h2>\n\nOnce the examination is done, everything goes to the <strong>underwriter</strong>. The underwriter reviews your application and exam results, in order to determine your <strong>insurance risk</strong>. Depending on the information you provide, they may request further information from you or your doctor.\n\nOnce that is done, they can make the decision as to how much coverage they can provide you, as well as the associated premium.\n\nOnce that''s done, all you have to do is wait for the letter.', 'Life Insurance Guide (Part VI) - Applying for Life Insurance', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'life-insurance-guide-part-vi-applying-for-life-insurance', '', '', '2015-11-10 21:00:43', '2015-11-10 21:00:43', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8771/nia/?p=154', 0, 'post', '', 0),
