(162, 2, '2015-11-11 21:28:35', '2015-11-11 21:28:35', 'It''s a sad but true fact that not all insurance applications are successful. Sometimes, the company you just spent all that time researching chooses not to offer you a policy. While rejection never feels good, it''s neither the end of the world, nor the end of the road.\n\n<h2>Don''t Forget to Re-Apply</h2>\n\nIt''s important to remember that not all insurance companies weight everything equally. So just because one company rejected your application does not mean that every other company will. Not only do different companies have different standards, but they also have different tolerance for risk. For example, one company may be more tolerant of diabetes than another.\n\nMany insurance brokers know which companies&nbsp;are better for a given condition, so they can help you determine which company is best suited for your particular circumstances.\n\nBest of all, if you re-apply quickly, you may be able to use the same medical examination for your second application, which can save both money and time.<strong></strong><em></em>\n\n<h2>Why Companies Reject Applications</h2>\n\nThe majority of life insurance application rejections are for medical or health-related reasons. The company is risking its money against your survival, so of course your health is of paramount importance.\n\n<h4>Health Reasons Why Companies Reject Applications</h4>\n\nLife insurance companies can reject your application for a host of reasons, often in combination. Here are some of the more common ones:\n\n<strong>*Because You Smoke</strong>\n\n<strong>*Your Weight</strong>\n\n<strong>*Pre-Existing Medical Conditions (such as Diabetes)</strong>\n\n<strong>*Drug Use (including Alcohol)</strong>\n\n<h4>Things You Can Do About It</h4>\n\nThe simplest thing you can do to increase your chance of having your insurance application approved is to <strong>quit smoking</strong>. This one step will do more than anything else for you.\n\nYou can also take the following steps:\n\n<strong>*Lose Weight</strong>\n\n<strong>*Exercise</strong>\n\n<strong>*Treat Any Pre-Existing Conditions</strong>\n\nEverything you can do to improve your overall health helps. There is a big difference in risk factor&nbsp;between controlled and uncontrolled diabetes.\n\n<h2>What Not To Do</h2>\n\nThe most important thing to remember when you re-apply for life insurance is to <strong>tell the truth</strong> about any medical and health conditions. Not only does sending false information invalidate your policy, it can also put you on a black list, and then you may find yourself unable to get life insurance from any provider. It simply isn''t worth it.\n\n<h2>What If They Still Say No</h2>\n\nIf you apply to several insurance companies, and they all turn you down, then it''s time to take a deeper look at the problem.\n\n<h4>Option 1: Try a Different Policy</h4>\n\nAs with anything else, sometimes you have to change your sights.&nbsp;If you keep getting rejected, maybe you need to consider a smaller benefit, or perhaps a shorter term. Little changes like this may be enough to turn your rejection into an acceptance. Also look at your <strong>riders</strong>, A rider is a policy option that allows for additional payouts under special circumstances such as accidents and illnesses.\n\n<h4>Option 2: Try to Change Your Lifestyle</h4>\n\nIf all else fails, take the time to change your <strong>lifestyle</strong>. Quit smoking, moderate your drinking, exercise more, and then re-apply. You cannot eliminate pre-existing conditions, but you can often mitigate their effects, and the only reason this option comes at the end of the list is because it takes more time.\n\nIt''s also the best option, even if you were accepted on your initial application.\n\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>', 'LIfe Insurance Guide (Part VII)  - Sometimes the Answer is No', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'life-insurance-guide-part-vii-sometimes-the-answer-is-no', '', '', '2015-11-11 21:28:35', '2015-11-11 21:28:35', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8771/nia/?p=162', 0, 'post', '', 0),
